<DOC><DOCNO> AP890917-0053 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1812EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-17 0323</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0332</SECOND><HEAD>Parts Of West Get Moisture After Dry Summer</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Rain fell across large areas of the West on Sunday, with someareas getting their first moisture in months.   In the Caribbean, Hurricane Hugo headed for the Virgin Islandsand Puerto Rico.   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the San FranciscoBay area of California into southern Oregon, from western Montanaacross Idaho, northern Nevada, northern Utah and western Wyoming,and over central Arizona,   In California, Santa Maria got its first measurable rainfallsince May, and since Saturday morning, San Diego had accumulated0.08 of an inch of rain, the city's first since June 10.   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from Florida acrossthe North Carolina coast, over western Pennsylvania and New Yorkstate, and over northern Maine.   Thunderstorms during the afternoon produced winds gusting to 55mph with small hail at St. Petersburg, Fla.   Miami warmed to a record 95 degrees, and on the northern Plains,Dickinson, N.D., hit a record 92.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 46degrees at Tahoe Valley, Calif., to 95 at Miami. Sunday's low forthe Lower 48 states was 26 at Gunnison, Colo.   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastalong the North Carolina and Georgia coasts. Showers were forecastfrom Montana across western Wyoming, western Colorado, Utah, Idahoand Nevada across the central coast of California.   Highs in the 50s were predicted over the northern Rockies; in the60s and 70s from New England across North Carolina, over the OhioValley and the Great Lakes, from the remainder of Montana acrosswestern Colorado and northern Arizona, from central Nevada acrossIdaho over southwestern California and from central Californiaacross Washington state; near 90 over Florida, the Gulf of MexicoCoast and much of Texas; in the 90s through the desert Southwest;and generally in the 80s over the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>